{"data":{"allMarkdownRemark":null,"markdownRemark":{"htmlAst":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"h2","properties":{"id":"modeling-distributed-consensus"},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"#modeling-distributed-consensus","ariaHidden":true,"className":["anchor"]},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"svg","properties":{"ariaHidden":"true","height":"16","version":"1.1","viewBox":"0 0 16 16","width":"16"},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"path","properties":{"fillRule":"evenodd","d":"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"},"children":[]}]}]},{"type":"text","value":"Modeling Distributed Consensus"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"strong","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Lamposk"}]},{"type":"text","value":" is a command-line based toy application that's meant to achieve distributed consensus in the context of purchasing tickets. In particular, the case study involves a single pool of tickets from which 5 kiosks (or servers/datacenters) pull their inventory from. A variable number of customers (clients) initiate transactions with the various kiosks at any given time, and its up to the system correctly handle the transactions to completion."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The system uses "},{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lamport%27s_bakery_algorithm","target":"_blank","rel":["nofollow","noopener","noreferrer"]},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Lamport's Bakery Algorithm"}]},{"type":"text","value":", which (generically speaking) describes a model for achieving mutual exclusion over a shared pool of resources. This means that a set of clearly established rules prevents any kiosk from selling a customer tickets that have already been sold, and thus no longer exist."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"This specific implementation is written in C. It uses "},{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"http://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man7/pthreads.7.html","target":"_blank","rel":["nofollow","noopener","noreferrer"]},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"pthreads"}]},{"type":"text","value":" for all of its thread handling, and C's socket library for all network communication. As a result, a nontrivial portion of the codebase is made up of just getting sockets to work without race conditions in a multi-threaded environment (I later decided to switch to using Java/RMI for the follow-up project to this, "},{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"/projects/raftosk"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Raftosk"}]},{"type":"text","value":")."}]}],"data":{"quirksMode":false}},"fields":{"slug":"/projects/lamposk"},"frontmatter":{"banner":{"childImageSharp":{"fluid":{"base64":"data:image/png;base64,","aspectRatio":2.1333333333333333,"src":"/static/b69c843fbf34eeccf3e87da51947a91e/d4f11/kiosk.png","srcSet":"/static/b69c843fbf34eeccf3e87da51947a91e/76268/kiosk.png 640w,\n/static/b69c843fbf34eeccf3e87da51947a91e/fb5f3/kiosk.png 1280w,\n/static/b69c843fbf34eeccf3e87da51947a91e/d4f11/kiosk.png 2560w","sizes":"(max-width: 2560px) 100vw, 2560px"}}},"logo":null,"title":"Lamposk","description":"Distributed ticketing kiosk implemented using Lamport's Bakery Algorithm","created":"2018-01-01T00:00:00.000Z","updated":"2018-01-01T00:00:00.000Z","feature":null,"draft":null,"tags":["Distributed Systems","Networking","Sockets","Multithreading","C","pthreads","CLI"],"git